{"id":"cond-mat/0505428","submitter":"Marianne Leitner","authors":"Marianne Leitner","title":"Zero Field Hall Effect in (2+1)-dimensional QED","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Adv. Theor. Math. Phys. 12 (2008), 479-491","doi":null,"report-no":"DIAS-STP-05-14","categories":"cond-mat.mes-hall hep-th math-ph math.MP","license":null,"abstract":"  In QED of two space dimensions, a quantum Hall effect occurs in the absence\nof any magnetic field. We give a simple and transparent explanation. In solid\nstate physics, the Hall conductivity for non-degenerate ground state is\nexpected to be given by an integer, the Chern number. In our field-free\nsituation, however, the conductivity is $\\pm 1/2$ in natural units. We fit this\nhalf-integral result into the topological setting and give a geometric\nexplanation reconciling the points of view of QFT and solid state physics. For\nquasi-periodic boundary conditions, we calculate the finite size correction to\nthe Hall conductivity. Applications to graphene and similar materials are\ndiscussed.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 17 May 2005 21:18:18 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 15 Jul 2005 21:34:10 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 8 Jul 2006 17:29:22 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Tue, 1 May 2007 16:21:01 GMT"},{"version":"v5","created":"Fri, 25 Apr 2008 13:53:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-04-25"}
